# Deploy to GitHub

**Repository:** [pramodmprasad/PMCA-Tools](https://github.com/pramodmprasad/PMCA-Tools)  
**Remote:** `https://github.com/pramodmprasad/PMCA-Tools.git`  
**Default branch:** `main`

On this machine, `git` may not be on PATH. Use the full executable when running commands for the user:

```powershell
& "C:\Program Files\Git\bin\git.exe" <subcommand> ...
```

## Standard publish workflow

1. From the project root: `pull` first if work might exist on GitHub or another clone.
2. `add` → `commit` with a clear message → `push` to `origin main`.

Example:

```powershell
Set-Location "e:\OneDrive - Pramod M P & Associates\Worklist\PMCA Tools"
& "C:\Program Files\Git\bin\git.exe" pull
& "C:\Program Files\Git\bin\git.exe" add -A
& "C:\Program Files\Git\bin\git.exe" commit -m "Describe the change"
& "C:\Program Files\Git\bin\git.exe" push
```

## Do not commit sensitive data

Respect `.gitignore`: never stage or force-add `Data/database.json`, `Data/DSC/`, `Data/Partnership/`, `node_modules/`, or `.env` files. If the user asks to push those paths, refuse and explain they must stay local or use private secure storage—not the public repo.

## New clone setup (reference)

After `git clone`, run `npm install` and restore local `Data/` files from a secure backup; they are not in the repository.
